# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: contour-plots
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] A **contour line** (also **isoline**, **isopleth**, isoquant or **isarithm**) of a function of two variables is a curve along which the function has a constant value, so that the curve joins points of equal value to the state.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] It is a plane section of the three-dimensional graph of the function $f(x,y)$ parallel to the $(x,y)$ -plane.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] More generally, a contour line for a function of two variables is a curve connecting points where the function has the same particular value.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In cartography, a contour line (often just called a "contour") joins points of equal elevation (height) above a given level, such as mean sea level.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] A **contour map** is a map illustrated with contour lines, for example a topographic map, which thus shows valleys and hills, and the steepness or gentleness of slopes.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The **contour interval** of a contour map is the difference in elevation between successive contour lines.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The gradient of the function is always perpendicular to the contour lines.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] When the lines are close together the magnitude of the gradient is large: the variation is steep.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] A level set is a generalization of a contour line for functions of any number of variables.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Contour lines are curved, straight or a mixture of both lines on a map describing the intersection of a real or hypothetical surface with one or more horizontal planes.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The configuration of these contours allows map readers to infer the relative gradient of a parameter and estimate that parameter at specific places.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In the latter case, the method of interpolation affects the reliability of individual isolines and their portrayal of slope, pits and peaks.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The idea of lines that join points of equal value was rediscovered several times.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The oldest known isobath (contour line of constant depth) is found on a map dated 1584 of the river Spaarne, near Haarlem, by Dutchman Pieter Bruinsz.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In 1701, Edmond Halley used such lines (isogons) on a chart of magnetic variation.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The Dutch engineer Nicholas Cruquius drew the bed of the river Merwede with lines of equal depth (isobaths) at intervals of 1 fathom in 1727, and Philippe Buache used them at 10-fathom intervals on a chart of the English Channel that was prepared in 1737 and published in 1752.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Such lines were used to describe a land surface (contour lines) in a map of the Duchy of Modena and Reggio by Domenico Vandelli in 1746, and they were studied theoretically by Ducarla in 1771, and Charles Hutton used them in the Schiehallion experiment.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Dupain-Triel used contour lines at 20-metre intervals, hachures, spot-heights and a vertical section.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In 1801, the chief of the French Corps of Engineers, Haxo, used contour lines at the larger scale of 1:500 on a plan of his projects for Rocca d'Anfo, now in northern Italy, under Napoleon.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] By around 1843, when the Ordnance Survey started to regularly record contour lines in Great Britain and Ireland, they were already in general use in European countries.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Isobaths were not routinely used on nautical charts until those of Russia from 1834, and those of Britain from 1838.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] As different uses of the technique were invented independently, cartographers began to recognize a common theme, and debated what to call these "lines of equal value" generally.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The word *isogram* (from Ancient Greek ἴσος*(isos)* 'equal' and γράμμα*(gramma)* 'writing, drawing') was proposed by Francis Galton in 1889 for lines indicating equality of some physical condition or quantity, though *isogram* can also refer to a word without a repeated letter.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Wright still preferred *isogram*, but it never attained wide usage.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] During the early 20th century, *isopleth* (πλῆθος, *plethos*, 'amount') was being used by 1911 in the United States, while *isarithm* (ἀριθμός, *arithmos*, 'number') had become common in Europe.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Additional alternatives, including the Greek-English hybrid *isoline* and *isometric line* (μέτρον, *metron*, 'measure'), also emerged.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Despite attempts to select a single standard, all of these alternatives have survived to the present.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] When maps with contour lines became common, the idea spread to other applications.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Perhaps the latest to develop are air quality and noise pollution contour maps, which first appeared in the United States in approximately 1970, largely as a result of national legislation requiring spatial delineation of these parameters.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Contour lines are often given specific names beginning with "*iso-*" according to the nature of the variable being mapped, although in many usages the phrase "contour line" is most commonly used.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Specific names are most common in meteorology, where multiple maps with different variables may be viewed simultaneously.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The prefix "'*iso-*" can be replaced with "*isallo-*" to specify a contour line connecting points where a variable changes at the same *rate* during a given time period.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isogon** (from Ancient Greek γωνία*(gonia)* 'angle') is a contour line for a variable which measures direction.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In meteorology and in geomagnetics, the term *isogon* has specific meanings which are described below.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isocline** (κλίνειν, *klinein*, 'to lean or slope') is a line joining points with equal slope.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In population dynamics and in geomagnetics, the terms *isocline* and *isoclinic line* have specific meanings which are described below.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] A curve of equidistant points is a set of points all at the same distance from a given point, line, or polyline.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In this case the function whose value is being held constant along a contour line is a distance function.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An example of an isopleth is population density, which can be calculated by dividing the population of a census district by the surface area of that district.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Each calculated value is presumed to be the value of the variable at the centre of the area, and isopleths can then be drawn by a process of interpolation.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The idea of an isopleth map can be compared with that of a choropleth map.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In meteorology, the word *isopleth* is used for any type of contour line.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Meteorological contour lines are based on interpolation of the point data received from weather stations and weather satellites.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Weather stations are seldom exactly positioned at a contour line (when they are, this indicates a measurement precisely equal to the value of the contour).
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Instead, lines are drawn to best approximate the locations of exact values, based on the scattered information points available.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Meteorological contour maps may present collected data such as actual air pressure at a given time, or generalized data such as average pressure over a period of time, or forecast data such as predicted air pressure at some point in the future.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Thermodynamic diagrams use multiple overlapping contour sets (including isobars and isotherms) to present a picture of the major thermodynamic factors in a weather system.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isobar** (from Ancient Greek βάρος*(baros)* 'weight') is a line of equal or constant pressure on a graph, plot, or map; an isopleth or contour line of pressure.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] More accurately, isobars are lines drawn on a map joining places of equal average atmospheric pressure reduced to sea level for a specified period of time.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In meteorology, the barometric pressures shown are reduced to sea level, not the surface pressures at the map locations.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The distribution of isobars is closely related to the magnitude and direction of the wind field, and can be used to predict future weather patterns.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Isobars are commonly used in television weather reporting.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An isopycnal is a line of constant density.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An *isoheight* or *isohypse* is a line of constant geopotential height on a constant pressure surface chart.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Isohypse and isoheight are simply known as lines showing equal pressure on a map.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isotherm** (from Ancient Greek θέρμη*(thermē)* 'heat') is a line that connects points on a map that have the same temperature.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Therefore, all points through which an isotherm passes have the same or equal temperatures at the time indicated.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An isotherm at 0 °C is called the freezing level.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The term *lignes isothermes* (or *lignes d'égale chaleur)* was coined by the Prussian geographer and naturalist Alexander von Humboldt, who as part of his research into the geographical distribution of plants published the first map of isotherms in Paris, in 1817.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] According to Thomas Hankins, the Scottish engineer William Playfair's graphical developments greatly influenced Alexander von Humbolt's invention of the isotherm.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Humbolt later used his visualizations and analyses to contradict theories by Kant and other Enlightenment thinkers that non-Europeans were inferior due to their climate.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isocheim** is a line of equal mean winter temperature, and an **isothere** is a line of equal mean summer temperature.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isohel** (ἥλιος, *helios*, 'Sun') is a line of equal or constant solar radiation.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isogeotherm** is a line of equal temperature beneath the Earth's surface.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isohyet** or **isohyetal line** (from Ancient Greek ὑετός*(huetos)* 'rain') is a line on a map joining points of equal rainfall in a given period.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] A map with isohyets is called an **isohyetal map**.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isohume** is a line of constant relative humidity, while an **isodrosotherm** (from Ancient Greek δρόσος*(drosos)* 'dew' and θέρμη*(therme)* 'heat') is a line of equal or constant dew point.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isoneph** is a line indicating equal cloud cover.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isochalaz** is a line of constant frequency of hail storms, and an **isobront** is a line drawn through geographical points at which a given phase of thunderstorm activity occurred simultaneously.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Snow cover is frequently shown as a contour-line map.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isotach** (from Ancient Greek ταχύς*(tachus)* 'fast') is a line joining points with constant wind speed.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In meteorology, the term **isogon** refers to a line of constant wind direction.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isopectic** line denotes equal dates of ice formation each winter, and an **isotac** denotes equal dates of thawing.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Contours are one of several common methods used to denote elevation or altitude and depth on maps.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] From these contours, a sense of the general terrain can be determined.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] They are used at a variety of scales, from large-scale engineering drawings and architectural plans, through topographic maps and bathymetric charts, up to continental-scale maps.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] "Contour line" is the most common usage in cartography, but isobath for underwater depths on bathymetric maps and **isohypse** for elevations are also used.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In cartography, the **contour interval** is the elevation difference between adjacent contour lines.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The contour interval should be the same over a single map.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] When calculated as a ratio against the map scale, a sense of the hilliness of the terrain can be derived.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Of course, to determine differences in elevation between two points, the contour interval, or distance in altitude between two adjacent contour lines, must be known, and this is normally stated in the map key.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Usually contour intervals are consistent throughout a map, but there are exceptions.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Sometimes intermediate contours are present in flatter areas; these can be dashed or dotted lines at half the noted contour interval.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] When contours are used with hypsometric tints on a small-scale map that includes mountains and flatter low-lying areas, it is common to have smaller intervals at lower elevations so that detail is shown in all areas.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Conversely, for an island which consists of a plateau surrounded by steep cliffs, it is possible to use smaller intervals as the height increases.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isopotential map** is a measure of electrostatic potential in space, often depicted in two dimensions with the electrostatic charges inducing that electric potential.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The term **equipotential line** or **isopotential line** refers to a curve of constant electric potential.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Whether crossing an equipotential line represents ascending or descending the potential is inferred from the labels on the charges.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In three dimensions, **equipotential surfaces** may be depicted with a two dimensional cross-section, showing equipotential lines at the intersection of the surfaces and the cross-section.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The general mathematical term level set is often used to describe the full collection of points having a particular potential, especially in higher dimensional space.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In the study of the Earth's magnetic field, the term **isogon** or **isogonic line** refers to a line of constant magnetic declination, the variation of magnetic north from geographic north.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **agonic line** is drawn through points of zero magnetic declination.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isoporic line** refers to a line of constant annual variation of magnetic declination .
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isoclinic line** connects points of equal magnetic dip, and an **aclinic line** is the isoclinic line of magnetic dip zero.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isodynamic line** (from δύναμις or *dynamis* meaning 'power') connects points with the same intensity of magnetic force.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Besides ocean depth, oceanographers use contour to describe diffuse variable phenomena much as meteorologists do with atmospheric phenomena.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In particular, **isobathytherms** are lines showing depths of water with equal temperature, **isohalines** show lines of equal ocean salinity, and **isopycnals** are surfaces of equal water density.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Various geological data are rendered as contour maps in structural geology, sedimentology, stratigraphy and economic geology.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Contour maps are used to show the below ground surface of geologic strata, fault surfaces (especially low angle thrust faults) and unconformities.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Isopach maps use **isopachs** (lines of equal thickness) to illustrate variations in thickness of geologic units.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In discussing pollution, density maps can be very useful in indicating sources and areas of greatest contamination.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Contour maps are especially useful for diffuse forms or scales of pollution.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Acid precipitation is indicated on maps with **isoplats**.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Some of the most widespread applications of environmental science contour maps involve mapping of environmental noise (where lines of equal sound pressure level are denoted **isobels**), air pollution, soil contamination, thermal pollution and groundwater contamination.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] By contour planting and contour ploughing, the rate of water runoff and thus soil erosion can be substantially reduced; this is especially important in riparian zones.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isoflor** is an isopleth contour connecting areas of comparable biological diversity.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Usually, the variable is the number of species of a given genus or family that occurs in a region.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Isoflor maps are thus used to show distribution patterns and trends such as centres of diversity.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In economics, contour lines can be used to describe features which vary quantitatively over space.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isochrone** shows lines of equivalent drive time or travel time to a given location and is used in the generation of isochrone maps.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isotim** shows equivalent transport costs from the source of a raw material, and an **isodapane** shows equivalent cost of travel time.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Contour lines are also used to display non-geographic information in economics.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] **Indifference curves** (as shown at left) are used to show bundles of goods to which a person would assign equal utility.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] An **isoquant** (in the image at right) is a curve of equal production quantity for alternative combinations of input usages, and an **isocost curve** (also in the image at right) shows alternative usages having equal production costs.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In political science an analogous method is used in understanding coalitions (for example the diagram in Laver and Shepsle's work).
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In population dynamics, an **isocline** shows the set of population sizes at which the rate of change, or partial derivative, for one population in a pair of interacting populations is zero.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In statistics, isodensity lines or isodensanes are lines that join points with the same value of a probability density.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Isodensanes are used to display bivariate distributions.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] For example, for a bivariate elliptical distribution the isodensity lines are ellipses.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Various types of graphs in thermodynamics, engineering, and other sciences use isobars (constant pressure), isotherms (constant temperature), isochors (constant specific volume), or other types of isolines, even though these graphs are usually not related to maps.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Such isolines are useful for representing more than two dimensions (or quantities) on two-dimensional graphs.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Common examples in thermodynamics are some types of phase diagrams.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In interpreting radar images, an **isodop** is a line of equal Doppler velocity, and an **isoecho** is a line of equal radar reflectivity.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In the case of hybrid contours, energies of hybrid orbitals and the energies of pure atomic orbitals are plotted.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The graph obtained is called hybrid contour.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] To maximize readability of contour maps, there are several design choices available to the map creator, principally line weight, line color, line type and method of numerical marking.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] If the contour lines are not numerically labeled and adjacent lines have the same style (with the same weight, color and type), then the direction of the gradient cannot be determined from the contour lines alone.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] However, if the contour lines cycle through three or more styles, then the direction of the gradient can be determined from the lines.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] The orientation of the numerical text labels is often used to indicate the direction of the slope.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Most commonly contour lines are drawn in plan view, or as an observer in space would view the Earth's surface: ordinary map form.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] However, some parameters can often be displayed in profile view showing a vertical profile of the parameter mapped.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Some of the most common parameters mapped in profile are air pollutant concentrations and sound levels.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In each of those cases it may be important to analyze (air pollutant concentrations or sound levels) at varying heights so as to determine the air quality or noise health effects on people at different elevations, for example, living on different floor levels of an urban apartment.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] In actuality, both plan and profile view contour maps are used in air pollution and noise pollution studies.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Labels are a critical component of elevation maps.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] A properly labeled contour map helps the reader to quickly interpret the shape of the terrain.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] If numbers are placed close to each other, it means that the terrain is steep.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Labels should be placed along a slightly curved line "pointing" to the summit or nadir, from several directions if possible, making the visual identification of the summit or nadir easy.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Contour labels can be oriented so a reader is facing uphill when reading the label.
[src:contour-plots/contour-line] Manual labeling of contour maps is a time-consuming process, however, there are a few software systems that can do the job automatically and in accordance with cartographic conventions, called automatic label placement.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] Suppose we have, as in contour advection, inferred knowledge of a single contour or isoline of an atmospheric constituent, *q* and we wish to validate this against satellite remote-sensing data.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] Since satellite instruments cannot measure the constituent directly, we need to perform some sort of inversion.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] In order to validate the contour, it is not necessary to know, at any given point, the exact value of the constituent.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] We only need to know whether it falls inside or outside, that is, is it greater than or less than the value of the contour, *q0*.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] This will be related to the satellite *measurement vector*, ${\vec {y}}$ , by some conditional probability, $P({\vec {y}}|j)$ , which we approximate by collecting samples, called *training data*, of both the measurement vector and the state variable, *q*.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] where *c* is the retrieved class at position, ${\vec {r}}$ .
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] Since this is the definition of maximum likelihood, a classification algorithm based on maximum likelihood is the most accurate method possible of validating an advected contour.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] A good method for performing maximum likelihood classification from a set of training data is variable kernel density estimation.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] There are two methods of generating the training data.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] The most obvious is empirically, by simply matching measurements of the variable, *q*, with collocated measurements from the satellite instrument.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] In this case, no knowledge of the actual physics that produce the measurement is required and the retrieval algorithm is purely statistical.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] where ${\vec {x}}$ is the *state vector* and *q = xk* is a single component.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] An advantage of this method is that state vectors need not reflect actual atmospheric configurations, they need only take on a state that could reasonably occur in the real atmosphere.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] There are also none of the errors inherent in most collocation procedures, e.g. because of offset errors in the locations of the paired samples and differences in the footprint sizes of the two instruments.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] Since retrievals will be biased towards more common states, however, the statistics ought to reflect those in the real world.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] The conditional probabilities, $P({\vec {y}}|j)$ , provide excellent error characterization, therefore the classification algorithm ought to return them.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] where *nc* is the number of classes (in this case, two).
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] If *C* is zero, then the classification is little better than chance, while if it is one, then it should be perfect.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] where *s* is the path, *l* is the length of the isoline and $C^{\prime }$ is the retrieved confidence as a function of position.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] While it appears that the integral must be evaluated separately for each value of the confidence rating, *C*, in fact it may be done for all values of *C* by sorting the confidence ratings of the results, $C^{\prime }$ .
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] The function relates the threshold value of the confidence rating for which the tolerance is applicable.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] That is, it defines a region that contains a fraction of the true isoline equal to the tolerance.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] The Advanced Microwave Sounding Unit (AMSU) series of satellite instruments are designed to detect temperature and water vapour.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] They have a high horizontal resolution (as little as 15 km) and because they are mounted on more than one satellite, full global coverage can be obtained in less than one day.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] Training data was generated using the second method from European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF) ERA-40 data fed to a fast radiative transfer model called RTTOV.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] The function, $\delta (C)$ has been generated from simulated retrievals and is shown in the figure to the right.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] This is then used to set the 90 percent tolerance in the figure below by shading all the confidence ratings less than 0.8.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] Thus we expect the true isoline to fall within the shading 90 percent of the time.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] Isoline retrieval is also useful for retrieving a continuum variable and constitutes a general, nonlinear inverse method.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] It has the advantage over both a neural network, as well as iterative methods such as optimal estimation that invert the forward model directly, in that there is no possibility of getting stuck in a local minimum.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] There are a number of methods of reconstituting the continuum variable from the discretized one.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] Once a sufficient number of contours have been retrieved, it is straightforward to interpolate between them.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] Conditional probabilities make a good proxy for the continuum value.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] The figure shows conditional probability versus specific humidity for the example retrieval discussed above.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] In other words, equal amounts of the "zeroeth order moment" lie on either side of *q*0.
[src:contour-plots/isoline-retrieval] This type of formulation is characteristic of a robust estimator.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] An **isosurface** is a three-dimensional analog of an isoline.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] It is a surface that represents points of a constant value (e.g. pressure, temperature, velocity, density) within a volume of space; in other words, it is a level set of a continuous function whose domain is 3-space.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] The term *isoline* is also sometimes used for domains of more than 3 dimensions.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] Isosurfaces are normally displayed using computer graphics, and are used as data visualization methods in computational fluid dynamics (CFD), allowing engineers to study features of a fluid flow (gas or liquid) around objects, such as aircraft wings.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] An isosurface may represent an individual shock wave in supersonic flight, or several isosurfaces may be generated showing a sequence of pressure values in the air flowing around a wing.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] Isosurfaces tend to be a popular form of visualization for volume datasets since they can be rendered by a simple polygonal model, which can be drawn on the screen very quickly.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] In medical imaging, isosurfaces may be used to represent regions of a particular density in a three-dimensional CT scan, allowing the visualization of internal organs, bones, or other structures.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] Numerous other disciplines that are interested in three-dimensional data often use isosurfaces to obtain information about pharmacology, chemistry, geophysics and meteorology.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] The marching cubes algorithm was first published in the 1987 SIGGRAPH proceedings by Lorensen and Cline, and it creates a surface by intersecting the edges of a data volume grid with the volume contour.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] Where the surface intersects the edge the algorithm creates a vertex.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] By using a table of different triangles depending on different patterns of edge intersections the algorithm can create a surface.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] This algorithm has solutions for implementation both on the CPU and on the GPU.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] The asymptotic decider algorithm was developed as an extension to marching cubes in order to resolve the possibility of ambiguity in it.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] The marching tetrahedra algorithm was developed as an extension to marching cubes in order to solve an ambiguity in that algorithm and to create higher quality output surface.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] The Surface Nets algorithm places an intersecting vertex in the middle of a volume voxel instead of at the edges, leading to a smoother output surface.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] The dual contouring algorithm was first published in the 2002 SIGGRAPH proceedings by Ju and Losasso, developed as an extension to both surface nets and marching cubes.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] It retains a dual vertex within the voxel but no longer at the center.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] Dual contouring leverages the position and normal of where the surface crosses the edges of a voxel to interpolate the position of the dual vertex within the voxel.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] This has the benefit of retaining sharp or smooth surfaces where surface nets often look blocky or incorrectly beveled.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] Dual contouring often uses surface generation that leverages octrees as an optimization to adapt the number of triangles in output to the complexity of the surface.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] Examples of isosurfaces are 'Metaballs' or 'blobby objects' used in 3D visualisation.
[src:contour-plots/isosurface] A more general way to construct an isosurface is to use the function representation.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] When the number of independent variables is two, a level set is called a **level curve**, also known as *contour line* or *isoline*; so a level curve is the set of all real-valued solutions of an equation in two variables *x*1 and *x*2.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] When *n* = 3, a level set is called a **level surface** (or *isosurface*); so a level surface is the set of all real-valued roots of an equation in three variables *x*1, *x*2 and *x*3.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] For higher values of n, the level set is a **level hypersurface**, the set of all real-valued roots of an equation in *n* > 3 variables (a higher-dimensional hypersurface).
[src:contour-plots/level-set] A level set is a special case of a fiber.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] Level sets show up in many applications, often under different names.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] For example, an implicit curve is a level curve, which is considered independently of its neighbor curves, emphasizing that such a curve is defined by an implicit equation.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] Analogously, a level surface is sometimes called an implicit surface or an isosurface.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] The name isocontour is also used, which means a contour of equal height.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] In various application areas, isocontours have received specific names, which indicate often the nature of the values of the considered function, such as isobar, isotherm, isogon, isochrone, isoquant and indifference curve.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] Consider the 2-dimensional Euclidean distance: $d(x,y)={\sqrt {x^{2}+y^{2}}}$ A level set $L_{r}(d)$ of this function consists of those points that lie at a distance of r from the origin, that make a circle.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] Geometrically, this means that the point $(3,4)$ lies on the circle of radius 5 centered at the origin.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] More generally, a sphere in a metric space $(M,m)$ with radius r centered at $x\in M$ can be defined as the level set $L_{r}(y\mapsto m(x,y))$ .
[src:contour-plots/level-set] A second example is the plot of Himmelblau's function shown in the figure to the right.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] Each curve shown is a level curve of the function, and they are spaced logarithmically: if a curve represents $L_{x}$ , the curve directly "within" represents $L_{x/10}$ , and the curve directly "outside" represents $L_{10x}$ .
[src:contour-plots/level-set] To understand what this means, imagine that two hikers are at the same location on a mountain.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] One of them is bold, and decides to go in the direction where the slope is steepest.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] The other one is more cautious and does not want to either climb or descend, choosing a path which stays at the same height.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] In our analogy, the above theorem says that the two hikers will depart in directions perpendicular to each other.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] A consequence of this theorem (and its proof) is that if f is differentiable, a level set is a hypersurface and a manifold outside the critical points of f.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] At a critical point, a level set may be reduced to a point (for example at a local extremum of f ) or may have a singularity such as a self-intersection point or a cusp.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] is called a **sublevel set** of *f* (or, alternatively, a **lower level set** or **trench** of *f*).
[src:contour-plots/level-set] is called a **superlevel set** of *f* (or, alternatively, an **upper level set** of *f*).
[src:contour-plots/level-set] Sublevel sets are important in minimization theory.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] By Weierstrass's theorem, the boundness of some non-empty sublevel set and the lower-semicontinuity of the function implies that a function attains its minimum.
[src:contour-plots/level-set] The convexity of all the sublevel sets characterizes quasiconvex functions.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] In computer graphics, **marching squares** is an algorithm that generates contours for a two-dimensional scalar field (rectangular array of individual numerical values).
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] A similar method can be used to contour 2D triangle meshes.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] Typical applications include the contour lines on topographic maps or the generation of isobars for weather maps.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] Note: Data equal to the isovalue has to be treated as *above* or *below* in a consistent way.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] Every 2x2 block of pixels in the binary image forms a contouring cell, so the whole image is represented by a grid of such cells (shown in green in the picture below).
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] Note that this contouring grid is one cell smaller in each direction than the original 2D field.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] Use the cell index to access a pre-built lookup table with 16 entries listing the edges needed to represent the cell (shown in the lower right part of the picture below).
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] Apply linear interpolation between the original field data values to find the exact position of the contour line along the edges of the cell.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] The contour is ambiguous at saddle points.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] The same basic algorithm can be applied to triangular meshes, which consist of connected triangles with data assigned to the vertices.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] For example, a scattered set of data points could be connected with a Delaunay triangulation to allow the data field to be contoured.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] A triangular cell is always *planar*, because it is a *2-simplex* (i.e. specified by *n*+1 vertices in an *n*-dimensional space).
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] There is always a unique linear interpolant across a triangle, and no possibility of an ambiguous saddle.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] The *data space* for the Marching Squares algorithm is 2D, because the vertices assigned a data value are connected to their neighbors in a 2D topological grid, but the spatial coordinates assigned to the vertices can be in 2D, 3D or higher dimensions.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] For example, a triangular mesh may represent a 2D data surface embedded in 3D space, where spatial positions of the vertices and interpolated points along a contour will all have 3 coordinates.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] Note that the case of squares is ambiguous again, because a quadrilateral embedded in 3-dimensional space is not necessarily planar, so there is a choice of geometrical interpolation scheme to draw the banded surfaces in 3D.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] The algorithm is embarrassingly parallel, because all cells are processed independently.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] A naive implementation of Marching Squares that processes every cell independently will perform every linear interpolation twice (isoline) or four times (isoband).
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] It is possible to reduce the computational overhead by caching the results of interpolation.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] For example, a single-threaded serial version would only need to cache interpolated results for one row of the input grid.
[src:contour-plots/marching-squares] It is also possible to reduce the size of the output by using indexed geometric primitives, *i.e.* create an array of 2D vertices and specify lines or polygons with short integer offsets into the array.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] A **two-dimensional space** is a mathematical space with two dimensions, meaning points have two degrees of freedom: their locations can be locally described with two coordinates or they can move in two independent directions.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] Common two-dimensional spaces are often called *planes* (especially the Euclidean plane), or, more generally, *surfaces*.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] These include analogs to physical spaces, like flat planes, and curved surfaces like spheres, cylinders, and cones, which can be infinite or finite.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] Some two-dimensional mathematical spaces are not used to represent physical positions, like an affine plane or complex plane.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] The most basic example is the flat Euclidean plane, an idealization of a flat surface in physical space such as a sheet of paper or a chalkboard.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] On the Euclidean plane, any two points can be joined by a unique straight line along which the distance can be measured.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] The space is flat because any two lines transversed by a third line perpendicular to both of them are parallel, meaning they never intersect and stay at uniform distance from each-other.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] Two-dimensional spaces can also be curved, for example the sphere and hyperbolic plane, sufficiently small portions of which appear like the flat plane, but on which straight lines which are locally parallel do not stay equidistant from each-other but eventually converge or diverge, respectively.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] Two-dimensional spaces with a locally Euclidean concept of distance but which can have non-uniform curvature are called Riemannian surfaces.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] Lorentzian surfaces look locally like a two-dimensional slice of relativistic spacetime with one spatial and one time dimension; constant-curvature examples are the flat Lorentzian plane (a two-dimensional subspace of Minkowski space) and the curved de Sitter and anti-de Sitter planes.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] Other types of mathematical planes and surfaces modify or do away with the structures defining the Euclidean plane.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] For example, the affine plane has a notion of parallel lines but no notion of distance; however, signed areas can be meaningfully compared, as they can in a more general symplectic surface.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] The projective plane does away with both distance and parallelism.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] A two-dimensional metric space has some concept of distance but it need not match the Euclidean version.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] A topological surface can be stretched, twisted, or bent without changing its essential properties.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] An algebraic surface is a two-dimensional set of solutions of a system of polynomial equations.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] Some mathematical spaces have additional arithmetical structure associated with their points.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] A vector plane is an affine plane whose points, called *vectors*, include a special designated origin or zero vector.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] Vectors can be added together or scaled by a number, and optionally have a Euclidean, Lorentzian, or Galilean concept of distance.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] The complex plane, hyperbolic number plane, and dual number plane each have points which are considered numbers themselves, and can be added and multiplied.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] A Riemann surface or Lorentz surface appear locally like the complex plane or hyperbolic number plane, respectively.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] Mathematical spaces are often defined or represented using numbers rather than geometric axioms.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] One of the most fundamental two-dimensional spaces is the real coordinate space, denoted $\mathbb {R} ^{2},$ consisting of pairs of real-number coordinates.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] Sometimes the space represents arbitrary quantities rather than geometric positions, as in the parameter space of a mathematical model or the configuration space of a physical system.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] More generally, other types of numbers can be used as coordinates.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] The complex plane is two-dimensional when considered to be formed from real-number coordinates, but one-dimensional in terms of complex-number coordinates.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] A two-dimensional complex space – such as the two-dimensional complex coordinate space, the complex projective plane, or a complex surface – has two complex dimensions, which can alternately be represented using four real dimensions.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] A two-dimensional lattice is an infinite grid of points which can be represented using integer coordinates.
[src:contour-plots/two-dimensional-space] Some two-dimensional spaces, such as finite planes, have only a finite set of elements.
